\end{align*}then determine the remainder when $a+b+c$ is divided by $13$.

response:
 Squiking this equation with $2$ we get $4ab+2bc+2ca\equiv 0\pmod{13}$. Subtracted from the last equation we obtain $3ab\equiv 8abc-2bc-2ca\pmod{13}$ or $ac\equiv 5ab-3bc-4ca\pmod{13}$. Thus, we get that $ab-ac\equiv 7bc\pmod{13}$ or $a\equiv 7b+c\pmod{13}$. Plugging into the first equation and expanding we have $bc(11c+8b-5a)\equiv 0\pmod{13}$. Since $(a,b,c)=(1,1,1)$ is not a solution we obtain $11c+8b-5a\equiv 0\pmod{13}$. Plugging in $a\equiv 7b+c\pmod{13}$ now yields $9b\equiv 16c\pmod{13}$ or $b\equiv 5c\pmod{13}$. So now we have a system of 2 equations \begin{align*}
a&\equiv 7b+c\pmod{13}\\
b&\equiv 5c\pmod{13}
\end{align*}For $c=1$ we get that $a+b+c\equiv 13\equiv 0\pmod{13}$. <answer> $\fbox{0}$ </answer>

